comments: I am severely underpaid for the work that I do. I have a Masters degree in the field of which I work (nutrition) and am only paid $19 an hour. Those in the same position as me in other cities such as Helena, Bozeman and Missoula are paid $27/hour ($8 more than me) to do the same job, just in another town. My position oversees 517 people in the BSB area as of May 2025, and there are only two employees taking care of that entire population, whereas Bozeman sees roughly double and has 6 people on staff. The office culture here is toxic and there are several "bullies". These people will go out of their way to harass other employees and make their jobs harder than necessary. This is my first full-time job post education and I do not think this is how a workplace environment should be.

supervisor_status: Supervisor and/or Manager: you are in a managerial position and are responsible for employeeÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s performance appraisals and approval of their leave, and may supervise one or more supervisors
comments: The health department has little support from the community and local government.  It feels like we are here to provide only the bare minimum mandated services, and the quality of our services has very little value.  We are also one of the lowest paid counties even though we are one of the largest communities in Montana.  The staff that we do still have work extremely hard and are poorly compensated for what they do, especially with the education and background they have.  New staff rarely stay, as there are much better opportunities elsewhere.  It's extremely hard to find motivation to continue to work in public health, even when you love it and feel very deeply that it is genuinely important.  I love my crew and am amazed at what they accomplish on a daily basis.  They do everything they can to take care of their community, and I do what I can to take care of them.  With our current budget cuts, we have also had many positions cut throughout the dept.  Morale is very low, and staff are scared.  People don't feel secure and are scared they may not have a job tomorrow.

comments: Our department experiences extremely high turnover rates. When I first started five years ago, there were five sanitarians. In the last four years, two of the original five retired and one moved into the open division manager position. Within these three open slots, we have had seven different sanitarians throughout the four years. This is an extremely high turnover rate. I have felt extremely discouraged at times feeling like I am constantly in "training mode", which takes much more time, effort, and energy than having experienced sanitarians. Additionally, our department has experienced frequent understaffing when these positions were open. For almost a year, our department was staffed at less than 50% with two sanitarians and a supervisor (full staffing being five sanitarians and a supervisor). This was a very stressful time in our office and left our department feeling quite burnt out. The only positive was the team we did have was a strong team and we were able to work well together and get things done fairly well as a team as well as individually.

comments:
When we all start by assuming positive intentions and show grace to everyone we work with, I believe it creates a highly productive and enjoyable work environment and atmosphere.

It's important to recognize and address situations without jumping to conclusions and making assumptions without sufficient evidence.

When situations arise and conclusions are made without thoroughly identifying and/or understanding the details or information from the individuals involved has led to misinterpretations and misunderstandings.

Gaining a broader perspective would be more beneficial and could avoid the impacts of negative relationships, unnecessary emotional distress and the breaking down of trust, as well as ineffective decision-making.
